article.headline: Sutton-Brown fuels Sting's comeback win
article.linkText: Sting climb out of a 14-point hole to beat Fever
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- With her team trailing by 14 points,
Tammy Sutton-Brown decided to get aggressive.

The Charlotte center had 18 points and seven rebounds, and the
Sting recovered to beat the Indiana Fever 70-59 on Friday.

"That start of the game, whew," Sutton-Brown said. "We
understand as a team to be successful we have to go inside and
outside. When we get the ball inside, things open up and we can be
successful."

Sutton-Brown made a jumper, blocked a shot and hit 1-of-2 free
throws on consecutive possessions to give the Sting a 62-57 lead
with 3:38 left.

Sutton-Brown's fifth block on Ebony Hoffman's shot with 1:36
left sealed it as the Sting (2-4) closed the game on a 19-4 run to
snap a two-game losing streak.

"It does a lot for our confidence, especially since Indiana is
a great team," Sutton-Brown said.

Anna DeForge and Hoffman had 14 points each for the Fever (5-3),
but star Tamika Catchings was held to nine points on 2-of-9
shooting as she was hounded all night by Sheri Sam and Tangela
Smith. The Fever, who have dropped three of four, were 5-0 when
Catchings played.

"Every single time I touched the ball there were two or three
people right there," Catchings said. "It's hard to play 1-on-3.
One of the things coach said was you may have to be the assists
leader this game. My team did a good job for the most part, but a
couple times when we needed scores, I should have stepped up and
taken a shot."

The Sting, who came in as the worst rebounding team in the WNBA,
had a 41-28 advantage on the boards. Smith had 11 rebounds to go
along with her 16 points.

"We had good spacing. We were patient," Sting coach Muggsy
Bogues said. "We were able to get the ball inside and get a lot of
production from Tammy and Tangela."

Indiana jumped out to the 15-1 lead as the Sting missed their
first 10 shots, while committing five turnovers. Tye'sha Fluker's
turnaround shot in the lane with 2:10 left in the first quarter was
Charlotte's first field goal.

But the Sting went on a 10-0 run early in the second quarter to
get back in it. Sam's layup with 10 seconds left put Charlotte
ahead 29-27 at halftime, its first lead of the game.

"We got a nice lead early in the game and then we let them back
in it by halftime," Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "When that
happens on the road, the home team gets excited about what they're
doing. It cost us in the end."

The Sting built the lead to 45-38 on Smith's two free throws
late in the third quarter. The Fever closed the quarter on an 8-2
run, getting within 47-46 on Tan White's driving layup in the final
minute.

Tamika Whitmore's 3-pointer with 7:45 left put Indiana ahead
55-51 before the Sting rallied.

"In the second half we had to fight to get back in it, but when
we did we would make a defensive mistake or give up too many
rebounds," DeForge said.
